>> B6: Describe a potential race in thread_set_priority() and explain
>> how your implementation avoids it.  Can you use a lock to avoid
>> this race?

Potential Race Condition in thread_set_priority
A race condition in thread_set_priority can occur when multiple threads simultaneously modify shared data structures, 
such as the donations list or the ready list, leading to inconsistent or incorrect priority values. Specifically, 
if one thread is setting its priority while another thread is modifying the donations list or the ready list, 
the resulting priority calculation might be incorrect. This could lead to improper thread scheduling and priority inversion.

Explanation of the Race Condition
1) Modifying cur->original_priority and cur->priority:
These assignments are straightforward, but if another thread were to simultaneously read or modify these values, it could result in inconsistent or incorrect priority settings.

2) Accessing and Modifying the Donations List:
The function accesses the donations list to find the highest priority donor and potentially updates the current thread's priority. 
If another thread simultaneously adds or removes elements from this list, it could lead to an incorrect priority being set for the current thread.

Our implementation avoid this by Disabling Interrupts:

At the beginning of the function we use
            enum intr_level old_level;
            old_level = intr_disable ();  // Disable interrupts to enter critical section
Interrupts are disabled at the beginning of the function to prevent other threads from preempting and causing race conditions. 
This ensures that no other thread can modify shared data structures like the donations list or the ready list while the current thread is setting its priority.

Locks can be used to avoid this race condition by ensuring mutual exclusion when modifying thread priorities. Specifically, when a thread calls thread_set_priority, 
it would first acquire a lock to enter the critical section, preventing other threads from simultaneously accessing shared data structures. After modifying the priorities, 
the thread would release the lock, allowing other threads to proceed. This method ensures that only one thread can modify priorities at a time, effectively preventing race conditions. 
However, to prevent interruptions during the lock operations, the lock acquire and release functions must disable interrupts within their critical sections.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> B7: Why did you choose this design?  In what ways is it superior to
>> another design you considered?


For priority scheduling, we first considered sorting the ready_list (of threads) every time there was a change in a thread’s priority, 
a new thread was created, before thread_yield(), before schedule(), before sema_up, etc. 
Then we would use list_pop_back to pop the thread with the highest priority because sorting will make sure that the thread with the
highest priority is the last thread in the ready_list. Although, this worked, we soon realized this added unnecessary complexity. 

Sorting the ready_list runs in O(nlogn)  (where n is the size of the list). Sorting every time in the aforementioned cases was 
unnecessary and unneeded because we just had to make sure that every time we scheduled a new thread to run, that thread had the 
highest priority with respect to all the other waiting threads. To do this, we realized we could use list_max on the 
ready_list to pop the thread with the highest priority instead of first sorting it and popping the last thread out.
List_max runs in O(n) time and so our design was much more efficient. 

